Subject: [PATCH 35/44] =?UTF-8?q?inline-3d(#625):=20revert=20the=20deviceP?=
 =?UTF-8?q?ixelRatio=20normalisation=20=E2=80=94=20units=20were=20already?=
 =?UTF-8?q?=20device=20px?=
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Instrumented on hardware (250% display):
  inline3d geom: raw_er=91,849 584x584 dsf=2.5 disp_px=3840x2160
                 pixel_m=8.964e-05 elem_h_m=0.0209 vdh=0.24 scene_layer=1

Both sides were already DEVICE pixels: display info reports the panel's device
resolution (3840x2160 -> pixel_m = 89.6um per device px) and
element_display_rect arrives in device px (584 = 234 css x 2.5). The earlier
"logical 1536x864" premise came from displayxr-cli selftest, a different code
path; the weave client reports device px.

So the normalisation shrank the element by the DPI scale: 584 x 89.6um =
0.0524 m (true) became 0.0209 m, which mis-placed the element AND inflated
m2v (0.24/0.0209 = 11.5 instead of 4.58), showing up as an over-scaled
off-axis skew (-15 measured; ~-5.3 is correct for a tile 13.8 cm off-centre
at 0.6 m).

NOTE (follow-up): this whole code path re-implements the Kooima math that the
runtime already owns and cube_handle_d3d11_win consumes via XR_DXR_view_rig
(chain XrDisplayRigDXR on xrLocateViews, render the returned XrView{pose,
fov}). Every geometry bug here has been a bug in that reimplementation. The
weave client has an OpenXR session and can locate views itself, so the right
end state is to delete this math and forward the runtime's render-ready
pose+fov — pending a per-locate canvas rect so the frustum can be scoped per
element rather than per bound window.
---
 .../blink/renderer/modules/xr/xr_session.cc   | 22 ++++++++-----------
 1 file changed, 9 insertions(+), 13 deletions(-)

diff --git a/third_party/blink/renderer/modules/xr/xr_session.cc b/third_party/blink/renderer/modules/xr/xr_session.cc
index 5dec6ad41cd76..27b1f8c66f8f9 100644
--- a/third_party/blink/renderer/modules/xr/xr_session.cc
+++ b/third_party/blink/renderer/modules/xr/xr_session.cc
@@ -2715,20 +2715,16 @@ void XRSession::UpdateInline3DViews() {
                             ? di.display_height_m / di.display_height_px
                             : 0.f;
 
-  // UNITS: the runtime reports the display in LOGICAL (DPI-scaled) pixels —
-  // e.g. 1536x864 for a 3840x2160 panel at 250% — so |pixel_m| is metres per
-  // LOGICAL pixel. But element_display_rect arrives in DEVICE pixels
+  // UNITS: both sides are DEVICE pixels and must stay that way — the display
+  // info reports the panel's device resolution (e.g. 3840x2160, so |pixel_m| is
+  // metres per device pixel) and element_display_rect arrives in device pixels
   // (getBoundingClientRect x dsf, rebased on a device-px ClientToScreen
-  // origin). Mixing them inflates every element dimension by the DPI scale:
-  // the element lands far off centre AND its physical height is wrong, so the
-  // m2v scene scale is wrong too — which shows up as a scene pinned to the
-  // wrong part of the display with wildly exaggerated disparity. Normalise the
-  // rect into the display's pixel space first.
-  const double dsf = DevicePixelRatioForInline3D();
+  // origin). Do NOT "normalise" by devicePixelRatio here: that shrinks the
+  // element by the DPI scale, which both mis-places it and inflates m2v
+  // (= virtualDisplayHeight / element height), and shows up as a scene in the
+  // wrong place with an over-scaled off-axis skew. Verified on a 250% display:
+  // raw rect 584px x 89.6um = 0.0524 m, the element's true height.
   gfx::RectF er_f(di.element_display_rect);
-  if (dsf > 0.0) {
-    er_f.Scale(static_cast<float>(1.0 / dsf));
-  }
   // TEMP DIAG (#625): which units actually arrive, and what geometry we derive.
   {
     static int s_geo_log = 0;
@@ -2736,7 +2732,7 @@ void XRSession::UpdateInline3DViews() {
       ++s_geo_log;
       const gfx::Rect& raw = di.element_display_rect;
       VLOG(1) << "[DisplayXR] inline3d geom: raw_er=" << raw.x() << "," << raw.y()
-              << " " << raw.width() << "x" << raw.height() << " dsf=" << dsf
+              << " " << raw.width() << "x" << raw.height()
               << " er_f=" << er_f.width() << "x" << er_f.height()
               << " disp_px=" << di.display_width_px << "x" << di.display_height_px
               << " pixel_m=" << pixel_m
